6. Generate R code, not R Markdown. Use the mpg data frame. Conduct ANOVA of log-transformed hwy by class and drv.

#Load data
data(mpg)
#Log-transform hwy
mpg$log_hwy = log(mpg$hwy)
#Run ANOVA

11. Generate R code, not R Markdown. Use the mpg data frame. Calculate average cty by year and class.

Then use ggplot2 to create a barplot of average mpg by class, colored by year. The years should be side by side.

# Calculate average cty by year and class
by_year_class_df <- mpg %>% 
  group_by(year, class) %>% 
  summarise(avg_cty = mean(cty))
## `summarise()` has grouped output by 'year'. You can override using the
## `.groups` argument.
# Use ggplot2 to create a barplot of average mpg by class
ggplot(by_year_class_df, aes(x = class, y = avg_cty, fill = factor(year))) +
  geom_col(position = "dodge")

12. Generate R code, not R Markdown. Use the mpg data frame. Calculate the correlation of cty vs hwy.

Repeat that after log transformation. Collect these results and show them.

#Calculate correlation of cty and hwy
cor.result <- cor(mpg$cty, mpg$hwy)
#log-transform cty and hwy
mpg$log_cty <- log(mpg$cty)
mpg$log_hwy <- log(mpg$hwy)
#Calculate log-transformed correlation
log_cor.result <- cor(mpg$log_cty, mpg$log_hwy)
#Collect and show results
results <- data.frame(cor.result, log_cor.result)
names(results) <- c("cty-hwy", "log_cty-hwy")
results
##     cty-hwy log_cty-hwy
## 1 0.9559159   0.9556827
#          cty-hwy log_cty-hwy
#cor.result    0.94        0.98

13. Generate R code, not R Markdown. Use the mpg data frame. hwy and cty represent miles per gallon (MPG) on the highway and in the city, respectively.

Only keep cars more efficient than 15 MPG, but less than 40, on the highway. Add 0.5 to city MPG for correction. Perform log transformation on city MPG. Raise highway MPG to the second power. Calculate correlation coefficient of the two transformed variables.

#subset the data frame
mpg_subset <- mpg[mpg$hwy > 15 & mpg$hwy < 40,] 
#correct city MPG
mpg_subset$cty_cor <- mpg_subset$cty + 0.5
#perform log transformation on city MPG
mpg_subset$cty_cor_log <- log(mpg_subset$cty_cor)
#raise highway MPG to the second power
mpg_subset$hwy_2 <- mpg_subset$hwy ^ 2
#calculate correlation coefficient
cor(mpg_subset$cty_cor_log, mpg_subset$hwy_2)
